$lang['How do you decode Hexadecimal?'] = 'O hlatholla bjang Hexadecimal?';
$lang['When it comes to decoding Hexadecimal, there are a few things you need to know. First, just like the decimal system, the hexadecimal system has 10 symbols (0-9) that represent numbers. However, in hexadecimal, these digits have values that are twice as large as their counterparts in the decimal system. So, while the number “10” is represented by the symbol “A” in hexadecimal, it would be equal to “10” in the decimal system.'] = 'Ge go tliwa tabeng ya go hlatholla Hexadecimal, go na le dilo tše mmalwa tšeo o swanetšego go di tseba. Sa pele, go swana le tshepedišo ya tesimale, tshepedišo ya heksadesimale e na le maswao a 10 (0-9) ao a emelago dinomoro. Le ge go le bjalo, ka heksadesimale, dinomoro tše di na le dikelo tšeo di fetago gabedi go feta balekane ba tšona tshepedišong ya tesimale. Ka gona, le ge palo ya “10” e emetšwe ke leswao la “A” ka hexadecimal, e be e tla lekana le “10” ka tshepedišong ya tesimale.';
$lang['Similarly, after reaching 9 in Hexadecimal (represented by “F”), we start counting again at 10 (“10”). This pattern continues until we reach 15 (“1F”), at which point we reset back to 0 and begin counting again at 16 (“20”). This might sound confusing at first, but with a little practice, it will become second nature!'] = 'Ka mo go swanago, ka morago ga go fihlelela 9 ka Hexadecimal (yeo e emetšwego ke “F”), re thoma go bala gape go 10 (“10”). Mokgwa wo o tšwela pele go fihlela re fihla go 15 (“1F”), mo nakong yeo re bušetša morago go 0 gomme ra thoma go bala gape go 16 (“20”). Se se ka kwagala se gakantšha mathomong, eupša ka go itlwaetša ganyenyane, e tla fetoga tlhago ya bobedi!';
